# Mnemosyne

Mnemosyne is an open-source, local-first notes application for iOS, macOS, Windows, and Android.

The product goal is simple: your notes live as plain Markdown files in a folder you choose, stay fully usable offline, and sync securely across your personal devices when you sign in to the same account.

## Principles

- Local-first by default
- Plain `.md` files in a user-owned folder
- Offline-first behavior on every platform
- End-to-end encrypted sync
- Open-source application and self-hosted infrastructure
- No operator access to note contents
- No data lock-in

## MVP Scope

The initial release is intentionally narrow:

- One user per account
- Personal device sync only
- Notes stored as normal Markdown files
- Folders and subfolders are supported
- External edits to Markdown files are detected and synced automatically
- File create, edit, rename, move, and delete operations sync across devices
- Deletes go to a synced trash
- Notes sync with end-to-end encryption
- Password loss does not allow service-side recovery of note contents
- Recovery key setup is required for account recovery
- Automatic background sync and manual sync are both available
- App settings sync across devices
- Local search is available on each device
- Tags and wikilinks are supported inside note content
- Backlinks and graph view are available locally

## Out Of Scope For MVP

- Shared notebooks
- Collaboration
- Attachments and binary file sync
- Plugin system
- Server-side note decryption
- Operator recovery of user note contents
- Version history beyond synced trash

## Open Source Boundary

This repository is intended to contain:

- Client applications
- Sync server
- Sync protocol
- AWS self-hosted deployment stack
- Documentation

This repository is not intended to contain:

- Managed hosting billing systems
- Managed hosting internal control plane
- Managed service operational glue that is not required for self-hosting

## Self-Hosted Deployment

The self-hosted path is designed for a single person deploying a personal sync service on AWS.

MVP assumptions:

- AWS is the only officially supported self-hosted target
- The CloudFormation deployment creates a single-account service
- The operator cannot decrypt note contents
- The deployment should favor low cost and simplicity over high scale

## Recommended Technical Direction

The implementation direction captured in this repository is:

- Client: Flutter for the shared app shell across desktop and mobile
- Shared core: Rust for sync, filesystem state, and cryptography
- Server: Go with a custom HTTPS API
- AWS self-hosted stack: CloudFormation for a simple single-user deployment

The architecture details and agent-facing implementation guidance live in:

- `ARCHITECTURE.md`
- `DEVELOPMENT.md`
- `AGENT.md`

